JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: Well--

00:17:02.310 --> 00:17:03.518
RICARDO HAUSMANN: Name a few.

00:17:03.518 --> 00:17:10.440
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: In Colombia,
we applied what some of us

00:17:10.440 --> 00:17:13.569
call, the third way.

00:17:13.569 --> 00:17:20.109
And that's what I would say Bill
Clinton did here, in the US.

00:17:20.109 --> 00:17:22.440
What Tony Blair did in the UK.

00:17:22.440 --> 00:17:24.780
What Fernando Henrique
Cardoso did in Brazil.

00:17:24.780 --> 00:17:28.500
Or Ricardo Lagos in Chile.

00:17:28.500 --> 00:17:34.050
You summarize the third
way in a phrase that

00:17:34.050 --> 00:17:39.450
says, more or less, that you
allow the markets to perform

00:17:39.450 --> 00:17:43.770
until they are able to perform.

00:17:43.770 --> 00:17:45.050
But you intervene.

00:17:45.050 --> 00:17:48.520
The state intervenes
when it's necessary.

00:17:48.520 --> 00:17:53.560
To correct whatever
markets are not doing,

00:17:53.560 --> 00:17:57.800
or when then the
markets do not work.

00:17:57.800 --> 00:18:04.090
And this pragmatic combination
has allowed the countries

00:18:04.090 --> 00:18:11.590
that have applied this third way
to have a period of prosperity

00:18:11.590 --> 00:18:14.710
that is much more important
than other periods

00:18:14.710 --> 00:18:17.830
in their economic history.

00:18:17.830 --> 00:18:23.580
In Venezuela, the approach
was completely different.

00:18:23.580 --> 00:18:25.820
The state has to do everything.

00:18:25.820 --> 00:18:28.550
The state has to
control everything.

00:18:28.550 --> 00:18:33.920
And not only in economic
terms, in political terms.

00:18:33.920 --> 00:18:39.680
So, freedom-- which is,
for me, a sacred word--

00:18:39.680 --> 00:18:41.240
was sacrificed in Venezuela.

00:18:41.240 --> 00:18:44.180
And when you sacrifice
freedom, and you

00:18:44.180 --> 00:18:49.160
don't allow the private
initiative and innovation

00:18:49.160 --> 00:18:55.310
and the good ideas
to flourish, you

00:18:55.310 --> 00:18:59.750
will simply destroy
whatever you have.

00:18:59.750 --> 00:19:02.090
And this is what has
happened in Venezuela.

00:19:02.090 --> 00:19:08.700
Plus, if you allow
corruption to take over,

00:19:08.700 --> 00:19:13.480
well, then you
make things worse.

00:19:13.480 --> 00:19:18.130
And unfortunately, Venezuela,
they also allowed corruption.

00:19:18.130 --> 00:19:23.200
To take over a system that
was doomed from the beginning

00:19:23.200 --> 00:19:27.287
because they were
on the wrong track.

00:19:27.287 --> 00:19:29.370
RICARDO HAUSMANN: Very
interesting, let's move on,

00:19:29.370 --> 00:19:30.160
now.

00:19:30.160 --> 00:19:33.880
You've got the Nobel
Prize for peace.

00:19:33.880 --> 00:19:39.070
So before we talk about
peace, let's talk about war.

00:19:39.070 --> 00:19:44.230
Colombia had a civil war
that was 50 some years long.

00:19:48.070 --> 00:19:51.850
What, in your mind, was
the cause of the war?

00:19:51.850 --> 00:19:55.030
And maybe not just the
cause of the war, but what

00:19:55.030 --> 00:19:56.710
made it so long lasting?

00:19:58.833 --> 00:20:00.250
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS:
Well, Colombia

00:20:00.250 --> 00:20:04.300
has been a very violent
country since our independence.

00:20:04.300 --> 00:20:07.600
We have had more civil
wars than any other country

00:20:07.600 --> 00:20:09.440
in Latin America.

00:20:09.440 --> 00:20:15.240
This specific war
with the FARC started

00:20:15.240 --> 00:20:20.310
in the early '60s,
when two things were

00:20:20.310 --> 00:20:22.290
present at same time.

00:20:22.290 --> 00:20:28.560
In the early '60s you had all
these revolutionary movements.

00:20:28.560 --> 00:20:33.570
The Cuban revolution and
the communist revolutions.

00:20:33.570 --> 00:20:38.520
And so you had the guerrilla
movements, not only in

00:20:38.520 --> 00:20:40.580
Colombia and also Venezuela.

00:20:40.580 --> 00:20:44.040
And in many countries.

00:20:44.040 --> 00:20:51.350
But in Colombia, after our
only military dictatorship--

00:20:51.350 --> 00:20:53.660
that in order to topple
this dictatorship

00:20:53.660 --> 00:20:57.950
that fortunately lasted very,
very short amount of time--

00:20:57.950 --> 00:21:03.380
the two main political parties
decided to share power.

00:21:03.380 --> 00:21:05.600
And share everything.

00:21:05.600 --> 00:21:09.310
And half of the cabinet it was
liberal, half of the cabinet

00:21:09.310 --> 00:21:10.610
was conservative.

00:21:10.610 --> 00:21:15.120
All the positions the
government, half and half.

00:21:15.120 --> 00:21:19.050
And they excluded
everybody else.

00:21:19.050 --> 00:21:23.820
So the revolutionary
movements plus the exclusion

00:21:23.820 --> 00:21:28.050
of what we called at that
time the National Front,

00:21:28.050 --> 00:21:37.020
gave the correct environment
for the FARC to flourish.

00:21:37.020 --> 00:21:42.900
And also we neglected
for many, many years,

00:21:42.900 --> 00:21:47.950
and we still are neglecting, the
development in the rural areas.

00:21:47.950 --> 00:21:53.560
And this was a rural
guerrilla, a peasant guerrilla.

00:21:53.560 --> 00:22:01.180
And when the guerrilla
movement started to fade away,

00:22:01.180 --> 00:22:04.170
or to win in other countries.

00:22:04.170 --> 00:22:10.580
And in Colombia,
unfortunately, something

00:22:10.580 --> 00:22:16.310
arrived that has been a
terrible problem for us,

00:22:16.310 --> 00:22:19.280
terrible headache, which
is drug trafficking.

00:22:19.280 --> 00:22:29.200
So the FARC discovered a golden
head of the drug trafficking

00:22:29.200 --> 00:22:31.540
to finance the war.

00:22:31.540 --> 00:22:36.160
So that gave them
an extra muscle.

00:22:36.160 --> 00:22:40.580
And so they were able
to last 50 years.

00:22:40.580 --> 00:22:46.780
And their idea was a
communist revolution.

00:22:46.780 --> 00:22:52.780
And their flag was
social justice.

00:22:52.780 --> 00:22:55.360
That's the origin.

00:22:55.360 --> 00:23:00.550
From there, they
started to evolve.

00:23:00.550 --> 00:23:03.650
Unfortunately, they got
into drug trafficking.

00:23:03.650 --> 00:23:07.110
And so their ideals
were starting to change.

00:23:09.780 --> 00:23:12.770
RICARDO HAUSMANN:
So before we go

00:23:12.770 --> 00:23:15.320
on to the continuation
of war and peace,

00:23:15.320 --> 00:23:18.140
maybe you could tell us a
little bit your thoughts

00:23:18.140 --> 00:23:28.700
about to what extent, in this
World War on drugs, that caused

00:23:28.700 --> 00:23:33.480
so much havoc in Colombia.

00:23:33.480 --> 00:23:36.265
Any thoughts on was this the
right way to face the drug

00:23:36.265 --> 00:23:36.765
issue?

00:23:39.870 --> 00:23:43.320
If you have any
comments on, was it

00:23:43.320 --> 00:23:47.010
inevitable that it should
have proceeded that way?

00:23:47.010 --> 00:23:50.250
Or were there other
ways in which,

00:23:50.250 --> 00:23:53.690
if you are now to
act on drug policy,

00:23:53.690 --> 00:23:56.030
what would your drug policy be?

00:23:56.030 --> 00:24:00.690
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: Well I
will tell you an anecdote.

00:24:00.690 --> 00:24:08.070
I am a very, very keen
reader of biographies.

00:24:08.070 --> 00:24:11.270
The latest biography
of Winston Churchill--

00:24:11.270 --> 00:24:14.650
it's a bit long it's a
bit over 1,000 pages,

00:24:14.650 --> 00:24:17.110
but it's the best one--

00:24:17.110 --> 00:24:24.670
has a story that during
prohibition, Winston Churchill

00:24:24.670 --> 00:24:30.220
came to the US through
Canada to California.

00:24:30.220 --> 00:24:35.090
And he arrived and
he asked for a drink.

00:24:35.090 --> 00:24:40.130
And they said, no
Mr. Churchill, drink

00:24:40.130 --> 00:24:43.280
is prohibited in this country.

00:24:43.280 --> 00:24:47.720
And he said, what a
strange country this is.

00:24:50.530 --> 00:24:56.970
You allow the huge profits
of the sale of liquor

00:24:56.970 --> 00:24:58.720
to go to the mafias.

00:24:58.720 --> 00:25:02.110
In my country, we give
it to the treasury.

00:25:02.110 --> 00:25:04.640
RICARDO HAUSMANN: [LAUGHING]

00:25:05.560 --> 00:25:11.270
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: That's
why it's interesting.

00:25:16.530 --> 00:25:19.320
RICARDO HAUSMANN: Now, you
have this guerrilla movement.

00:25:19.320 --> 00:25:23.100
It's there, it's outside of
the constitutional rules.

00:25:23.100 --> 00:25:26.460
I mean, you change the
Constitution in 1991,

00:25:26.460 --> 00:25:29.130
I believe.

00:25:29.130 --> 00:25:33.270
You know, that system that
justified the creation

00:25:33.270 --> 00:25:35.280
of the guerrilla was change.

00:25:35.280 --> 00:25:37.230
You became a more open
democracy and so on.

00:25:37.230 --> 00:25:40.950
But the guerrillas continued.

00:25:40.950 --> 00:25:44.865
So here, you are they appoint
you minister of defense.

00:25:47.470 --> 00:25:51.230
What's your strategy, how
do you deal with them?

00:25:51.230 --> 00:25:53.690
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS:
Well, I go back.

00:25:53.690 --> 00:25:56.990
I was seeing them and they
were showing me around

00:25:56.990 --> 00:26:02.550
and how President
Kennedy was a sailor.

00:26:02.550 --> 00:26:05.120
And I was in the Navy, also.

00:26:05.120 --> 00:26:10.700
And I learned in the
Navy, how to sail.

00:26:10.700 --> 00:26:12.890
And the first lesson
that they gave me,

00:26:12.890 --> 00:26:16.920
the officer that
was in charge said,

00:26:16.920 --> 00:26:19.970
Santos, he gave
a small sailboat,

00:26:19.970 --> 00:26:22.300
go and learn how to sail.

00:26:22.300 --> 00:26:25.880
And that was very difficult.
I didn't know what to do

00:26:25.880 --> 00:26:29.180
and I really got problems.

00:26:29.180 --> 00:26:32.150
And he said, I'll
teach you something

00:26:32.150 --> 00:26:35.240
which is going to be
very important to you.

00:26:35.240 --> 00:26:40.250
Not only to learn how to
sail, but in your life.

00:26:40.250 --> 00:26:44.090
In everything that has
to do with your future.

00:26:44.090 --> 00:26:48.950
You always need to know
where you want to go.

00:26:48.950 --> 00:26:53.510
And in sailing, if you have,
like, a port of destination,

00:26:53.510 --> 00:26:55.070
you can use all the winds.

00:26:55.070 --> 00:26:58.490
No matter how strong they are
or if they're against you,

00:26:58.490 --> 00:27:04.160
you can use them to arrive
to that port of destination.

00:27:04.160 --> 00:27:09.200
That was a very good lesson
that many, many years later

00:27:09.200 --> 00:27:12.230
in a conversation, I
had with Nelson Mandela.

00:27:12.230 --> 00:27:16.010
I was the chairman of the
UNCTAD, United Nations

00:27:16.010 --> 00:27:17.690
Conference on Trade
and Development.

00:27:17.690 --> 00:27:22.400
And he got elected
chairman after me.

00:27:22.400 --> 00:27:28.550
So I went to Johannesburg,
and I gave him the chair.

00:27:28.550 --> 00:27:31.820
That morning, I was in
the hotel in Johannesburg

00:27:31.820 --> 00:27:34.310
and I turned on the television.

00:27:34.310 --> 00:27:40.550
And I saw the most
incredible life program.

00:27:40.550 --> 00:27:44.920
There were the victims of the
war with the perpetrators,

00:27:44.920 --> 00:27:49.130
live in television,
confronting each other.

00:27:49.130 --> 00:27:54.080
Some of them embraced, others
screamed at each other.

00:27:54.080 --> 00:27:56.240
And I couldn't understand.

00:27:56.240 --> 00:28:00.440
And I had a 15 minute
meeting with Mandela program

00:28:00.440 --> 00:28:02.570
that afternoon.

00:28:02.570 --> 00:28:05.480
I went and I asked
him, what is it

00:28:05.480 --> 00:28:08.940
that I was seeing this
morning on television?

00:28:08.940 --> 00:28:13.400
And that 15 minutes became
five hours of conversation

00:28:13.400 --> 00:28:15.040
about peace.

00:28:15.040 --> 00:28:18.170
And at the end he
said, your country

00:28:18.170 --> 00:28:23.620
will never progress if
you don't end the war.

00:28:23.620 --> 00:28:26.440
And then I discovered
at that time,

00:28:26.440 --> 00:28:28.930
that that was going to be
my port of destination.

00:28:28.930 --> 00:28:32.850
That was early '90s.

00:28:32.850 --> 00:28:37.130
So, when I became
minister of defense,

00:28:37.130 --> 00:28:41.450
I already knew that
we needed peace.

00:28:41.450 --> 00:28:46.360
But to have a successful
peace process,

00:28:46.360 --> 00:28:49.990
you need to have the right
conditions, the necessary

00:28:49.990 --> 00:28:51.610
conditions.

00:28:51.610 --> 00:28:54.580
And one of them was
to weaken the FARC.

00:28:54.580 --> 00:28:58.630
To convince them that
through violence,

00:28:58.630 --> 00:29:00.610
they will never achieve
their objective.

00:29:00.610 --> 00:29:02.290
They will never win.

00:29:02.290 --> 00:29:08.230
And so you have to be
successful militarily

00:29:08.230 --> 00:29:10.870
in order to take them to
the negotiating table.

00:29:10.870 --> 00:29:15.940
And so when I arrived, when
I was appointed minister

00:29:15.940 --> 00:29:19.900
of defense, I knew that
I had to be successful

00:29:19.900 --> 00:29:24.090
if I wanted to take them
to the negotiating table.

00:29:24.090 --> 00:29:28.910
So I had to become a
very effective hawk.

00:29:28.910 --> 00:29:32.600
And I was elected
president in the year 2010

00:29:32.600 --> 00:29:34.790
because I was a war hero.

00:29:34.790 --> 00:29:39.890
And when you were
a war hero, you

00:29:39.890 --> 00:29:44.310
exercise a very easy
type of leadership.

00:29:44.310 --> 00:29:48.100
In times of war,
you give orders.

00:29:48.100 --> 00:29:51.510
And you rally the
forces around you.

00:29:51.510 --> 00:29:55.890
And you point at the
enemy, your adversaries,

00:29:55.890 --> 00:30:02.490
and you say, let's go
together against our enemies.

00:30:02.490 --> 00:30:04.080
That is easy.

00:30:04.080 --> 00:30:07.860
But then I have
to become a dove.

00:30:07.860 --> 00:30:09.760
And that is much more
difficult. That's

00:30:09.760 --> 00:30:12.380
why I say it's much more
difficult to make peace

00:30:12.380 --> 00:30:13.570
than to make war.

00:30:13.570 --> 00:30:17.530
Because to make peace, the type
of leadership is not vertical,

00:30:17.530 --> 00:30:19.030
it's horizontal.

00:30:19.030 --> 00:30:22.030
Instead of giving orders,
you have to persuade.

00:30:22.030 --> 00:30:26.650
You have to convince the victims
of the war, of the conflict,

00:30:26.650 --> 00:30:28.900
to forgive.

00:30:28.900 --> 00:30:34.030
And then to tell the
mother of two kids,

00:30:34.030 --> 00:30:38.740
or a daughter that had
been raped and killed,

00:30:38.740 --> 00:30:43.570
to forgive the perpetrators,
that is much more difficult.

00:30:43.570 --> 00:30:47.740
And to heal the wounds
of 50 years of war

00:30:47.740 --> 00:30:49.540
takes a lot of time.

00:30:49.540 --> 00:30:55.540
But I always knew
that being effective

00:30:55.540 --> 00:30:58.870
as a minister of defense
was necessary to be

00:30:58.870 --> 00:31:03.760
able to sit down and have
a serious negotiation.

00:31:06.770 --> 00:31:11.200
So when I was
minister of defense,

00:31:11.200 --> 00:31:16.510
I also learned a
very important lesson

00:31:16.510 --> 00:31:21.050
about how to wage
an effective war.

00:31:21.050 --> 00:31:27.110
When I came into
the ministry, we

00:31:27.110 --> 00:31:30.110
had copied military strategies.

00:31:30.110 --> 00:31:35.960
And we had a terrible way of
measuring the effectiveness

00:31:35.960 --> 00:31:39.230
of our officers.

00:31:39.230 --> 00:31:42.290
We copied that from Vietnam.

00:31:42.290 --> 00:31:45.570
The body count, how
many bodies do you have?

00:31:45.570 --> 00:31:51.620
And that's what the generals
and colonels were measured by.

00:31:51.620 --> 00:31:54.770
And that is a very bad way
to measure the effectiveness

00:31:54.770 --> 00:31:59.780
of a an officer.

00:31:59.780 --> 00:32:07.210
And one general who had retired,
very intelligent historian,

00:32:07.210 --> 00:32:11.200
when I was recently appointed
as minister of defense.

00:32:11.200 --> 00:32:14.860
He said to me,
Mr. Santos, you're

00:32:14.860 --> 00:32:17.120
going to have to wage war.

00:32:17.120 --> 00:32:19.480
Lead the war against the FARC.

00:32:19.480 --> 00:32:22.680
But don't treat them
as your enemies,

00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:26.010
treat them as your adversaries.

00:32:26.010 --> 00:32:28.800
Enemies, you destroy.

00:32:28.800 --> 00:32:32.580
Your adversaries, you beat.

00:32:32.580 --> 00:32:35.580
And you're going to
have to live with them

00:32:35.580 --> 00:32:37.050
for the rest of your life.

00:32:37.050 --> 00:32:41.970
I know that you want
peace, so treat them

00:32:41.970 --> 00:32:47.640
as sons of the same nation.

00:32:47.640 --> 00:32:50.290
They are your brothers.

00:32:50.290 --> 00:32:54.010
Humanize the war.

00:32:54.010 --> 00:32:57.820
And that will give
you much more respect.

00:32:57.820 --> 00:33:04.330
And will give the military more
respect from the population.

00:33:04.330 --> 00:33:11.360
Our military were blacklisted
in many of the lists

00:33:11.360 --> 00:33:15.850
in the human rights in
Geneva And New York.

00:33:15.850 --> 00:33:20.560
So we've made a radical change.

00:33:20.560 --> 00:33:25.570
And for example, instead of
a body count, I start saying,

00:33:25.570 --> 00:33:29.800
I will measure your
performance by the number

00:33:29.800 --> 00:33:33.680
of guerrillas that give up.

00:33:33.680 --> 00:33:35.240
Give their arms.

00:33:35.240 --> 00:33:38.360
That reincorporate
into civil society.

00:33:38.360 --> 00:33:44.520
And we did some very audacious
programs, put in place

00:33:44.520 --> 00:33:46.140
with very audacious policies.

00:33:46.140 --> 00:33:55.200
Like, for example, we identified
the mothers and the fathers

00:33:55.200 --> 00:33:56.640
of many of the guerrillas.

00:33:56.640 --> 00:33:59.310
And asked them to
write a message

00:33:59.310 --> 00:34:03.570
to their sons or daughters.

00:34:03.570 --> 00:34:10.320
And we put these
messages in some balls

00:34:10.320 --> 00:34:12.960
that floated in the rivers.

00:34:12.960 --> 00:34:16.530
That flowed down to where the
guerrillas were concentrated,

00:34:16.530 --> 00:34:18.480
in the Amazon jungle.

00:34:18.480 --> 00:34:23.489
And this became for them,
a tremendous incentive

00:34:23.489 --> 00:34:26.610
to go and see if their
mother or their father

00:34:26.610 --> 00:34:28.320
had sent them a message.

00:34:28.320 --> 00:34:30.300
And afterwards, when I
negotiated with them,

00:34:30.300 --> 00:34:32.250
after the peace
process, they said,

00:34:32.250 --> 00:34:37.860
you cannot imagine how it
was much harder for us,

00:34:37.860 --> 00:34:40.889
as commanders.

00:34:40.889 --> 00:34:45.030
The morale of our people, what
you did with these messages.

00:34:45.030 --> 00:34:51.179
And we also put some lights
in the trees in the jungle

00:34:51.179 --> 00:34:52.739
during Christmas.

00:34:52.739 --> 00:34:55.199
With messages from
the fathers, mothers

00:34:55.199 --> 00:34:57.150
or, sisters of the guerrillas.

00:34:57.150 --> 00:34:59.640
And we left, and then
the guerrillas came

00:34:59.640 --> 00:35:04.830
and they all competed to
see who had the message.

00:35:04.830 --> 00:35:11.760
And the effect on the war,
of humanizing the war,

00:35:11.760 --> 00:35:16.050
was much higher.

00:35:16.050 --> 00:35:22.870
Had a much bigger impact
than bombing the camps

00:35:22.870 --> 00:35:25.330
and killing everybody.

00:35:25.330 --> 00:35:29.220
So that is a human
way to win a war.

00:35:29.220 --> 00:35:34.580
And that allowed me,
afterwards, to sit down

00:35:34.580 --> 00:35:40.650
in a much better environment
to negotiate peace.

00:35:40.650 --> 00:35:44.660
RICARDO HAUSMANN: So
when did you decide

00:35:44.660 --> 00:35:48.291
to move from war to peace?

00:35:48.291 --> 00:35:50.333
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: When
I got elected president.

00:35:53.510 --> 00:36:04.070
Because I had identified the
conditions that were necessary.

00:36:04.070 --> 00:36:10.610
I used a lot of the lessons
that I learned here, at Harvard.

00:36:10.610 --> 00:36:14.300
Negotiation lessons, the
first lessons I took,

00:36:14.300 --> 00:36:19.830
was from a professor
called Roger Fisher.

00:36:19.830 --> 00:36:23.040
One of his pupils,
William Murray,

00:36:23.040 --> 00:36:26.520
I brought in as a special
advisor for the negotiations

00:36:26.520 --> 00:36:27.887
since the very beginning.

00:36:30.620 --> 00:36:40.780
And I also used the lessons of
a marvelous professor, whose

00:36:40.780 --> 00:36:45.130
100th anniversary was
just recently celebrated,

00:36:45.130 --> 00:36:46.900
Richard Newstead.

00:36:46.900 --> 00:36:49.780
Vise President Gore was
there in the celebration

00:36:49.780 --> 00:36:52.120
of his 100th anniversary.

00:36:52.120 --> 00:36:56.290
And I studied all
the peace processes

00:36:56.290 --> 00:36:58.780
that have been negotiated.

00:36:58.780 --> 00:37:04.840
What was applicable to our
process, and what was not.

00:37:04.840 --> 00:37:07.000
What lessons could we learn?

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:09.550
And so, in that
process, I discovered

00:37:09.550 --> 00:37:12.850
a series of conditions
that were necessary.

00:37:12.850 --> 00:37:17.260
And one of them was
that in today's world,

00:37:17.260 --> 00:37:22.330
asymmetrical wars need
the support of the region.

00:37:22.330 --> 00:37:26.090
And if possible, of the
international community.

00:37:26.090 --> 00:37:31.360
We were going to negotiate peace
under the umbrella of the Rome

00:37:31.360 --> 00:37:34.300
statute, which is an
international treaty that

00:37:34.300 --> 00:37:38.620
was negotiated to
facilitate negotiations.

00:37:38.620 --> 00:37:42.400
And those conditions
were not present

00:37:42.400 --> 00:37:43.660
until I became president.

00:37:43.660 --> 00:37:47.880
When I made peace, for
example, with ChÃ¡vez.

00:37:47.880 --> 00:37:52.030
Or with Korea, in order
to be able to have

00:37:52.030 --> 00:37:54.970
the necessary conditions to
have a successful peace process.

00:37:54.970 --> 00:38:00.970
So I switched from hawk to
dove when I became president.

00:38:00.970 --> 00:38:03.360
RICARDO HAUSMANN: And so
tell us a little bit more.

00:38:03.360 --> 00:38:10.450
So you decided to
go to a negotiation.

00:38:10.450 --> 00:38:14.140
What was your
initial strategy, how

00:38:14.140 --> 00:38:17.020
did you conceive of the
negotiating process?

00:38:17.020 --> 00:38:18.520
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS:
In this process,

00:38:18.520 --> 00:38:20.080
of learning from
other processes.

00:38:20.080 --> 00:38:26.530
And all my predecessors had
tried to make peace since 1882.

00:38:26.530 --> 00:38:30.370
All the presidents of Colombia
had tried and had failed.

00:38:30.370 --> 00:38:37.240
So I started to study why had
they failed, what was lacking.

00:38:37.240 --> 00:38:42.700
The first thing that I learned,
not only from our own failures,

00:38:42.700 --> 00:38:44.500
but from other peace
processes, that you

00:38:44.500 --> 00:38:51.750
need a very short
and concrete agenda.

00:38:51.750 --> 00:38:57.320
I learned that the less
public your negotiations,

00:38:57.320 --> 00:39:00.430
especially at the
beginning, the better.

00:39:00.430 --> 00:39:06.130
So we negotiated secretly
for two years, the agenda.

00:39:06.130 --> 00:39:10.110
And until we had the agenda,
which is of almost 50%

00:39:10.110 --> 00:39:14.100
of negotiations, defined,
then we went public.

00:39:14.100 --> 00:39:19.170
We went to Oslo and
made the agenda public.

00:39:19.170 --> 00:39:25.070
I learned that the military
were very important to be

00:39:25.070 --> 00:39:26.390
part of the process.

00:39:26.390 --> 00:39:29.420
All my predecessors thought
that the military would

00:39:29.420 --> 00:39:34.990
be spoilers of the process.

00:39:34.990 --> 00:39:42.310
But I also learned that there's
a very famous phrase of General

00:39:42.310 --> 00:39:48.180
MacArthur, said, if you think
that the military like war,

00:39:48.180 --> 00:39:50.320
you don't understand
the military.

00:39:50.320 --> 00:39:52.960
The soldiers are the ones
who risked their lives.

00:39:52.960 --> 00:39:57.310
They are the most
interested in having peace.

00:39:57.310 --> 00:40:00.920
And I know because I
was in the military.

00:40:00.920 --> 00:40:04.100
And so I talk their language.

00:40:04.100 --> 00:40:05.380
So I brought them in.

00:40:05.380 --> 00:40:11.740
Two of my chief negotiators were
the two most popular generals

00:40:11.740 --> 00:40:15.160
that Colombia had,
police and army.

00:40:15.160 --> 00:40:23.000
And so all these conditions
could not be sort of created

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:24.680
until I was president.

00:40:24.680 --> 00:40:29.180
That's why the switch was
made when I became president.

00:40:29.180 --> 00:40:33.970
Two years of secret
negotiations and then we

00:40:33.970 --> 00:40:38.240
start the public negotiations.

00:40:38.240 --> 00:40:41.890
Another very difficult
decision that I took

00:40:41.890 --> 00:40:49.750
was, because during the
Ministry of Defense,

00:40:49.750 --> 00:40:52.930
we had been able to
get the upper hand

00:40:52.930 --> 00:40:57.780
in the military balance of
power with the guerrillas.

00:40:57.780 --> 00:41:00.720
Because the
guerrillas had always

00:41:00.720 --> 00:41:04.440
taken advantage of
the negotiations

00:41:04.440 --> 00:41:09.390
to increase their military
and their political power.

00:41:09.390 --> 00:41:15.270
I studied the peace processes
in Israel and Palestine.

00:41:15.270 --> 00:41:19.590
And I remembered a strategy
that Prime Minister

00:41:19.590 --> 00:41:25.640
Rabin, from Israel, had applied
when he sat down with Arafat.

00:41:25.640 --> 00:41:33.100
And he said, I will
negotiate with terrorism,

00:41:33.100 --> 00:41:39.720
which was Arafat, as if
there is no terrorism.

00:41:39.720 --> 00:41:42.630
But I will continue
to fight terrorism as

00:41:42.630 --> 00:41:45.120
if there is no peace process.

00:41:45.120 --> 00:41:50.120
So I told the FARC, I'm going
to apply the same doctrine.

00:41:50.120 --> 00:41:54.330
We will sit down and negotiate,
but we continue the war.

00:41:54.330 --> 00:41:57.420
They wanted a
ceasefire, but I did not

00:41:57.420 --> 00:42:02.640
want a ceasefire until I knew
that we could get an agreement.

00:42:02.640 --> 00:42:04.350
It's very risky.

00:42:04.350 --> 00:42:07.740
It brought me a lot of
problems because people

00:42:07.740 --> 00:42:08.580
don't understand.

00:42:08.580 --> 00:42:11.270
Why are you talking
to these people

00:42:11.270 --> 00:42:14.310
while they committed
all these atrocities?

00:42:14.310 --> 00:42:18.600
But in the long run, it's
the most effective way

00:42:18.600 --> 00:42:22.240
to get a result.

00:42:22.240 --> 00:42:24.310
RICARDO HAUSMANN: What
was your initial thoughts

00:42:24.310 --> 00:42:27.910
of what you were going to find
in the FARC in the negotiation?

00:42:27.910 --> 00:42:29.620
And what did you
learn about the FARC

00:42:29.620 --> 00:42:31.115
through the negotiation process?

00:42:37.770 --> 00:42:41.880
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS:
They, in a way,

00:42:41.880 --> 00:42:44.040
were getting older,
the grinders.

00:42:44.040 --> 00:42:48.570
And another condition
that was necessary

00:42:48.570 --> 00:42:52.050
was to convince the
commanders that it's

00:42:52.050 --> 00:42:58.240
in their own personal
advantage to negotiate, and not

00:42:58.240 --> 00:43:00.280
to continue the war.

00:43:00.280 --> 00:43:05.500
When I became minister of
defense, 45 years of war,

00:43:05.500 --> 00:43:09.280
and not one single
member of what they call,

00:43:09.280 --> 00:43:12.670
the secretariat, like,
the board of directors,

00:43:12.670 --> 00:43:14.170
had been captured or killed.

00:43:14.170 --> 00:43:18.240
Not one single one, in 45 years.

00:43:18.240 --> 00:43:23.790
They had penetrated all
our intelligence agencies.

00:43:23.790 --> 00:43:28.980
So I went to a
friend of mine, which

00:43:28.980 --> 00:43:32.040
was the prime minister of
Great Britain at that time.

00:43:32.040 --> 00:43:34.500
And I told him, please help me.

00:43:34.500 --> 00:43:36.130
And he said, what do you need?

00:43:36.130 --> 00:43:39.060
I said, I need you
to help me in what

00:43:39.060 --> 00:43:43.410
you are the best in the
world, intelligence.

00:43:43.410 --> 00:43:50.640
So he got the phone
and dialed the phone

00:43:50.640 --> 00:43:54.900
number of a marvelous man
called Sir John Scarlett.

00:43:54.900 --> 00:43:58.740
He was the head of MI6,
British intelligence.

00:43:58.740 --> 00:44:03.090
He said, I have a friend of
mine, I want you to help him.

00:44:03.090 --> 00:44:09.435
I went in his building, it's
a building with no address.

00:44:09.435 --> 00:44:13.020
And I had a crash course in
intelligence for two days.

00:44:13.020 --> 00:44:15.600
Incredible crash
course that said,

00:44:15.600 --> 00:44:17.880
you need to change
your intelligence.

00:44:17.880 --> 00:44:22.710
You need to change the way
the intelligence operates.

00:44:22.710 --> 00:44:26.580
Your intelligence is
modeled by the Americans.

00:44:26.580 --> 00:44:30.150
The Americans have
their agencies compete.

00:44:30.150 --> 00:44:33.200
FBI against the CIA
against the DEA.

00:44:33.200 --> 00:44:34.890
They all compete.

00:44:34.890 --> 00:44:36.060
That won't work in Colombia.

00:44:36.060 --> 00:44:40.170
That doesn't work in Colombia
because your intelligence is

00:44:40.170 --> 00:44:41.670
made by the different forces.

00:44:41.670 --> 00:44:44.790
And they are military
or police, and they

00:44:44.790 --> 00:44:47.070
don't have the flexibility.

00:44:47.070 --> 00:44:49.950
You have to have a
system like we have,

00:44:49.950 --> 00:44:53.370
concentrated under the
Office of the Prime Minister.

00:44:53.370 --> 00:44:55.830
This case, on the
office of the president.

00:44:55.830 --> 00:45:00.510
This change made
our intelligence

00:45:00.510 --> 00:45:02.010
much more effective.

00:45:02.010 --> 00:45:08.400
And we started the
taking down what we call,

00:45:08.400 --> 00:45:11.610
the high value targets.

00:45:11.610 --> 00:45:15.480
And I had to make very
difficult decisions.

00:45:15.480 --> 00:45:24.540
For example, one day I was
having dinner with I remember,

00:45:24.540 --> 00:45:29.940
the board of directors of
Conservation International

00:45:29.940 --> 00:45:33.720
Environmental, NGO.

00:45:33.720 --> 00:45:36.510
And the commander of the
Army called me and said,

00:45:36.510 --> 00:45:44.870
we have located the number one
person in FARC, the commander.

00:45:44.870 --> 00:45:50.120
We've been going after him
for 40 years or 30 years.

00:45:50.120 --> 00:45:52.640
And I had to take a decision.

00:45:52.640 --> 00:45:56.210
I had already started
the peace process.

00:45:56.210 --> 00:46:00.430
But the rules of the
game were Rabin doctrine.

00:46:00.430 --> 00:46:03.820
So I had to take the
decision right there.

00:46:03.820 --> 00:46:06.550
Do I authorize an
operation against him?

00:46:06.550 --> 00:46:13.220
This could simply erase
the peace process forever.

00:46:13.220 --> 00:46:18.890
Or a do I withhold, and tell
the military now, you know,

00:46:18.890 --> 00:46:20.360
you can't go after him?

00:46:20.360 --> 00:46:25.070
Which could mean
that the military

00:46:25.070 --> 00:46:27.260
would be very frustrated.

00:46:27.260 --> 00:46:33.550
And their support for the peace
process would be weakened.

00:46:33.550 --> 00:46:36.166
Well, I took the decision
to authorize the operation.

00:46:39.980 --> 00:46:45.130
Because I had told the FARC,
it is legitimate for you

00:46:45.130 --> 00:46:47.500
to want to kill me.

00:46:47.500 --> 00:46:51.070
In those words, it
is legitimate for me

00:46:51.070 --> 00:46:52.540
to go to the war against you.

00:46:52.540 --> 00:46:54.830
And they had accepted.

00:46:54.830 --> 00:46:57.080
So I said, go after him.

00:46:57.080 --> 00:46:57.945
He was killed.

00:46:57.945 --> 00:47:01.170
And afterwards.

00:47:01.170 --> 00:47:06.320
The FARC told me,
it hurt us a lot.

00:47:06.320 --> 00:47:07.840
You're an SOB.

00:47:07.840 --> 00:47:10.690
But we respect you for that.

00:47:10.690 --> 00:47:18.670
And that helped the trust that
was necessary, in their case,

00:47:18.670 --> 00:47:24.160
to be built in order to be
able to get an agreement.

00:47:24.160 --> 00:47:34.000
I learned that also,
like humanizing the war,

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:36.290
also humanizes your adversaries.

00:47:36.290 --> 00:47:42.690
So they're human beings
with son, with the families.

00:47:42.690 --> 00:47:48.100
And that allows you to start
speaking a different language,

00:47:48.100 --> 00:47:50.530
with a different attitude.

00:47:50.530 --> 00:47:53.470
Of course, we were
miles apart in the way

00:47:53.470 --> 00:47:56.740
we thought about the
future of the country.

00:47:56.740 --> 00:48:02.710
But slowly, I realized that
what they were asking for

00:48:02.710 --> 00:48:10.490
was not that important, if
you weighed the concessions.

00:48:10.490 --> 00:48:15.710
They wanted to have a
representation in Congress.

00:48:15.710 --> 00:48:22.940
They wanted to be
forgiven for their crimes.

00:48:22.940 --> 00:48:26.830
And I said, the base would
be forgiven, not the leaders.

00:48:26.830 --> 00:48:29.870
The leaders will be judged,
sentenced, and condemned.

00:48:29.870 --> 00:48:32.090
There will be no impunity.

00:48:32.090 --> 00:48:36.170
Because the Rome statute
will not allow the impunity.

00:48:36.170 --> 00:48:43.030
They wanted to have some
reforms in the rural areas, that

00:48:43.030 --> 00:48:47.500
were exactly the same that
were needed for the country.

00:48:47.500 --> 00:48:50.200
So I said, OK
that, I can accept.

00:48:50.200 --> 00:48:54.130
So I discovered
that there was not

00:48:54.130 --> 00:48:57.370
huge differences in what
their expectations were,

00:48:57.370 --> 00:48:58.660
and what we could give.

00:48:58.660 --> 00:49:04.520
And that facilitated
the negotiations a lot.

00:49:04.520 --> 00:49:08.130
RICARDO HAUSMANN: Why
did it take so long?

00:49:08.130 --> 00:49:09.690
How long did it take?

00:49:09.690 --> 00:49:12.110
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: It took
six years of negotiations.

00:49:12.110 --> 00:49:16.920
And this a very good question.

00:49:16.920 --> 00:49:21.972
When people ask me, what would
you have done differently?

00:49:21.972 --> 00:49:23.930
One of the things I would
have done differently

00:49:23.930 --> 00:49:30.170
is, we negotiated five
points in the agenda.

00:49:30.170 --> 00:49:35.300
And we decided to
negotiate in a sequence.

00:49:35.300 --> 00:49:40.670
We have to agree
on the first point

00:49:40.670 --> 00:49:42.710
to go to the second point.

00:49:42.710 --> 00:49:44.280
That was a mistake.

00:49:44.280 --> 00:49:51.110
We should have negotiated
simultaneously because time,

00:49:51.110 --> 00:49:53.990
and that is the lesson that
I learned afterwards, goes

00:49:53.990 --> 00:49:57.680
against the government,
not against the guerrillas.

00:49:57.680 --> 00:50:00.320
And because everything
that happens

00:50:00.320 --> 00:50:03.680
in the negotiation, will
cost the government,

00:50:03.680 --> 00:50:09.320
or the person
representing the state,

00:50:09.320 --> 00:50:11.690
will cost him politically.

00:50:11.690 --> 00:50:13.730
Especially when
you are negotiating

00:50:13.730 --> 00:50:15.890
in the middle of the war.

00:50:15.890 --> 00:50:21.440
And that cost me a lot
of my political capital

00:50:21.440 --> 00:50:24.340
because it went on too long.

00:50:24.340 --> 00:50:26.280
But that's a good question.

00:50:26.280 --> 00:50:29.570
They knew that,
and they stalled.

00:50:29.570 --> 00:50:33.770
And they were slow
in taking decisions.

00:50:33.770 --> 00:50:36.538
And there, I would have
done it differently.

00:50:39.620 --> 00:50:41.270
RICARDO HAUSMANN: Very good.

00:50:41.270 --> 00:50:46.010
In this country there, is a
huge debate on health care.

00:50:49.120 --> 00:50:53.170
There's, you know,
in this country,

00:50:53.170 --> 00:50:58.360
most health insurance is
provided by employers.

00:50:58.360 --> 00:51:00.160
And then when
people switch jobs,

00:51:00.160 --> 00:51:03.280
it generates
uncertainty and so on.

00:51:06.340 --> 00:51:10.180
It's very expensive.

00:51:10.180 --> 00:51:12.400
It's been on the political
agenda for a long time.

00:51:15.080 --> 00:51:21.880
Colombia made a major,
major health care reform.

00:51:21.880 --> 00:51:23.490
can you tell us--

00:51:23.490 --> 00:51:26.940
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: Very
shortly, what we did was,

00:51:26.940 --> 00:51:32.850
we passed a constitutional
amendment saying,

00:51:32.850 --> 00:51:36.150
access to the health system
is a fundamental right.

00:51:36.150 --> 00:51:39.300
No hospital can deny
access to any Colombian

00:51:39.300 --> 00:51:42.630
who goes there sick.

00:51:42.630 --> 00:51:46.380
Also, they were a system
that was subsidized,

00:51:46.380 --> 00:51:49.290
and a system that
was by contributions.

00:51:49.290 --> 00:51:54.360
We decided to put the
passengers of second class

00:51:54.360 --> 00:51:57.510
as passengers of first class.

00:51:57.510 --> 00:52:05.740
And we chose the treatments that
were included in the system.

00:52:05.740 --> 00:52:11.950
I think we overdid it, our
system is too expensive.

00:52:11.950 --> 00:52:14.910
And so we have a
system today that

00:52:14.910 --> 00:52:18.600
measured, by
international standards,

00:52:18.600 --> 00:52:21.810
they have three ways of
measuring the health system.

00:52:21.810 --> 00:52:25.290
What percentage of the
population is covered?

00:52:25.290 --> 00:52:28.470
In the case of Columbia,
universal coverage.

00:52:28.470 --> 00:52:30.590
How many treatments are
included the system?

00:52:30.590 --> 00:52:35.130
The case of Columbia, very,
very high amount of treatment.

00:52:35.130 --> 00:52:37.360
Very large amount of treatments.

00:52:37.360 --> 00:52:41.340
And what percentage of the
family income goes to health?

00:52:41.340 --> 00:52:43.830
We have one of the
lowest in the world.

00:52:43.830 --> 00:52:47.130
So we are very well
rated, our health system.

00:52:47.130 --> 00:52:49.830
Of course, we have
terrible problems

00:52:49.830 --> 00:52:51.450
in the quality of the system.

00:52:51.450 --> 00:52:55.110
We have to prove
that and we might

00:52:55.110 --> 00:52:58.030
have to reduce the
number of treatments.

00:52:58.030 --> 00:53:03.150
But Ricardo, I think I
am the journalist here.

00:53:03.150 --> 00:53:05.580
You're not a
journalist then, right?

00:53:05.580 --> 00:53:08.280
And I think many
people here would

00:53:08.280 --> 00:53:11.280
like to hear about Venezuela.

00:53:11.280 --> 00:53:15.840
You're from Venezuela, you
are the expert on Venezuela.

00:53:15.840 --> 00:53:18.175
Can I ask you some
questions about Venezuela?

00:53:18.175 --> 00:53:19.050
RICARDO HAUSMANN: OK.

