you think will be needed
to recover a country that

00:53:44.120 --> 00:53:47.030
has been destroyed?

00:53:47.030 --> 00:53:48.980
In many respects,
institutionally,

00:53:48.980 --> 00:53:51.830
and the productive sector.

00:53:51.830 --> 00:53:55.060
What will it take?

00:53:55.060 --> 00:54:02.615
RICARDO HAUSMANN: Well let
me take a short seven hour

00:54:02.615 --> 00:54:03.115
stretch.

00:54:03.115 --> 00:54:04.930
[LAUGHTER]

00:54:06.010 --> 00:54:10.010
I would say, first of all,
the catastrophe in Venezuela

00:54:10.010 --> 00:54:13.540
is really a orders of magnitude.

00:54:13.540 --> 00:54:18.210
Bigger than anything that we've
seen pretty much anywhere.

00:54:18.210 --> 00:54:21.390
And certainly, nowhere
in this continent.

00:54:21.390 --> 00:54:23.815
The US Great Depression,
GDP fell by 29%.

00:54:28.720 --> 00:54:31.240
I mean, that was
a historic event.

00:54:31.240 --> 00:54:33.880
People think that they
ignore our depression

00:54:33.880 --> 00:54:39.510
because they went through the
great recession of 2008, 2009.

00:54:39.510 --> 00:54:43.520
That saw a decline in GDP of 3%.

00:54:43.520 --> 00:54:45.180
The Great Depression, was 29%.

00:54:48.410 --> 00:54:55.100
Venezuela had two times the
Great Depression by 2018.

00:54:55.100 --> 00:54:59.630
Between 2013 and 2014,
it was a collapse

00:54:59.630 --> 00:55:02.690
of twice the Great Depression.

00:55:02.690 --> 00:55:06.500
And in 2019, the
expectation is that it

00:55:06.500 --> 00:55:09.387
will be a 30% decline in GDP.

00:55:09.387 --> 00:55:10.970
So, it'll be another
Great Depression.

00:55:10.970 --> 00:55:12.810
Sort of three great depressions.

00:55:12.810 --> 00:55:13.310
So--

00:55:13.310 --> 00:55:16.530
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:55:16.530 --> 00:55:18.450
RICARDO HAUSMANN: So--

00:55:18.450 --> 00:55:20.890
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:55:20.890 --> 00:55:23.520
RICARDO HAUSMANN: I'll
let you speak afterwards.

00:55:23.520 --> 00:55:24.687
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: Do you--

00:55:24.687 --> 00:55:26.936
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:55:33.835 --> 00:55:35.460
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS:
Continue, continue.

00:55:35.460 --> 00:55:37.335
RICARDO HAUSMANN: No,
no, you're journalists.

00:55:37.335 --> 00:55:42.240
Anyway, so, the
collapse is enormous.

00:55:42.240 --> 00:55:47.230
This collapse has
essentially two causes.

00:55:47.230 --> 00:55:50.110
And it's the two things
that we need to fix.

00:55:50.110 --> 00:55:53.680
The first one is that
Venezuelans have been

00:55:53.680 --> 00:55:56.500
disempowered from any rights.

00:55:56.500 --> 00:56:00.400
You were mentioning before,
you have no right to own,

00:56:00.400 --> 00:56:04.270
things can be expropriated
from you with no justification.

00:56:04.270 --> 00:56:06.890
And mostly, no compensation.

00:56:06.890 --> 00:56:08.350
You don't have the
right to import.

00:56:08.350 --> 00:56:10.090
You don't have the right
to buy foreign exchange.

00:56:10.090 --> 00:56:11.715
You don't have the
right to set prices.

00:56:14.220 --> 00:56:16.180
Or you don't even have
the right to decide

00:56:16.180 --> 00:56:19.870
who you sell things to.

00:56:19.870 --> 00:56:23.350
So you have a society that
has been disempowered.

00:56:23.350 --> 00:56:25.415
People have needs.

00:56:25.415 --> 00:56:27.040
Some people would
like to make a living

00:56:27.040 --> 00:56:29.380
out of supplying those needs.

00:56:29.380 --> 00:56:31.680
They don't have the
rights to do that.

00:56:31.680 --> 00:56:33.760
And this all happened
when the price of oil

00:56:33.760 --> 00:56:36.840
was still above 100.

00:56:36.840 --> 00:56:41.460
So the system was undermining
the basic economy.

00:56:41.460 --> 00:56:44.390
The second thing that happened
is that in that period,

00:56:44.390 --> 00:56:48.590
where the disempowered society,
they say, well, you know,

00:56:48.590 --> 00:56:50.750
if production declines,
it's not a problem.

00:56:50.750 --> 00:56:53.710
Because we can import.

00:56:53.710 --> 00:56:57.300
And imports went up by a
lot because the price of oil

00:56:57.300 --> 00:56:57.820
was high.

00:56:57.820 --> 00:57:00.400
But in addition, they
borrowed enormously.

00:57:00.400 --> 00:57:03.670
And they were spending
as if the price of oil

00:57:03.670 --> 00:57:07.120
was at 200, when it was at 100.

00:57:07.120 --> 00:57:09.310
So at some point in time,
capital markets said,

00:57:09.310 --> 00:57:11.470
we don't lend to
this country anymore.

00:57:11.470 --> 00:57:13.310
So they couldn't
borrow that amount.

00:57:13.310 --> 00:57:15.310
And that's what triggered
the initial recession.

00:57:15.310 --> 00:57:16.810
And then the price
of oil collapsed.

00:57:16.810 --> 00:57:19.560
So now, there's a shortage
of foreign exchange.

00:57:19.560 --> 00:57:21.910
So there's no raw materials,
no intermediate inputs,

00:57:21.910 --> 00:57:23.320
no spare parts.

00:57:23.320 --> 00:57:25.420
So people cannot produce.

00:57:25.420 --> 00:57:26.700
They cannot plant.

00:57:26.700 --> 00:57:30.730
So there's no seeds, no
fertilizers, no agrochemicals.

00:57:30.730 --> 00:57:33.118
There are no spare parts, or
there's no transportation.

00:57:33.118 --> 00:57:33.910
There are no buses.

00:57:33.910 --> 00:57:34.630
There are no trucks.

00:57:34.630 --> 00:57:35.410
There's no cars.

00:57:35.410 --> 00:57:36.880
There's no motorcycles.

00:57:36.880 --> 00:57:37.450
Because--

00:57:37.450 --> 00:57:40.990
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: Let me
ask you a specific question.

00:57:40.990 --> 00:57:45.430
Pompeo, the Secretary of
State, was in Cucutan, Colombia

00:57:45.430 --> 00:57:46.480
just two days ago.

00:57:46.480 --> 00:57:47.397
RICARDO HAUSMANN: Yes.

00:57:47.397 --> 00:57:50.290
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: And he said
the recovery of Venezuela will

00:57:50.290 --> 00:57:54.460
cost about $6-$10 billion.

00:57:54.460 --> 00:57:58.930
You think with $10 billion
you can reconstruct Venezuela?

00:57:58.930 --> 00:58:01.270
RICARDO HAUSMANN: I think
he was off by a 0 or so.

00:58:01.270 --> 00:58:03.490
[LAUGHTER]

00:58:03.490 --> 00:58:07.300
But if he were right,
if he could do that,

00:58:07.300 --> 00:58:09.460
he would deserve the
Nobel Prize in economics.

00:58:09.460 --> 00:58:12.190
Because he will have
discovered a way

00:58:12.190 --> 00:58:14.020
to solve the
problems of the world

00:58:14.020 --> 00:58:15.280
for a tenth of their cost.

00:58:15.280 --> 00:58:18.160
But it will be
very, very expensive

00:58:18.160 --> 00:58:19.690
to recover the country.

00:58:19.690 --> 00:58:22.480
But I sense that there
is a lot of willingness

00:58:22.480 --> 00:58:25.690
to help Venezuela recover.

00:58:25.690 --> 00:58:26.620
But I--

00:58:26.620 --> 00:58:28.078
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS:
To what extent?

00:58:28.078 --> 00:58:31.270
And forgive me for
asking this question,

00:58:31.270 --> 00:58:34.840
but you're in Venezuela and
you've been very involved.

00:58:38.480 --> 00:58:44.890
The political use of
the Venezuelan drama

00:58:44.890 --> 00:58:54.220
has been, in a way, a bad
thing for finding a solution.

00:58:54.220 --> 00:58:58.270
What we saw, for example,
with the humanitarian aid.

00:58:58.270 --> 00:59:01.840
And both president
of the United States,

00:59:01.840 --> 00:59:05.080
the president of Colombia
using that politically

00:59:05.080 --> 00:59:09.000
for their own electorate here.

00:59:09.000 --> 00:59:12.472
Do you think that it has
been good or it has been bad?

00:59:12.472 --> 00:59:14.680
RICARDO HAUSMANN: Well, I
think that in this country,

00:59:14.680 --> 00:59:19.540
there's broad bipartisan
support for the restoration

00:59:19.540 --> 00:59:21.550
of democracy in Venezuela.

00:59:21.550 --> 00:59:25.180
And, you know, you've
seen statements

00:59:25.180 --> 00:59:27.490
on both sides of the aisle.

00:59:27.490 --> 00:59:31.710
So I hope this does not
become partisan in the US.

00:59:31.710 --> 00:59:37.240
Because this is really an issue
of democracy and human rights

00:59:37.240 --> 00:59:41.930
and freedom and the restoration
of the Constitution.

00:59:41.930 --> 00:59:48.650
And it's an area where both
Democrats and Republicans share

00:59:48.650 --> 00:59:49.610
values.

00:59:49.610 --> 00:59:57.020
So I certainly hope
that it remains an issue

00:59:57.020 --> 00:59:59.510
with broad bipartisan support.

00:59:59.510 --> 01:00:03.770
I mean, you know, it has
the enthusiastic support

01:00:03.770 --> 01:00:08.420
of prime minister
Trudeau in Canada.

01:00:08.420 --> 01:00:09.805
It has broad support of--

01:00:09.805 --> 01:00:11.305
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS:
All around, yes.

01:00:11.305 --> 01:00:11.880
RICARDO HAUSMANN: All along.

01:00:11.880 --> 01:00:14.120
So I think that that broad
coalition is something

01:00:14.120 --> 01:00:15.792
that we need to keep together.

01:00:19.020 --> 01:00:22.556
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: And
the thing that [AUDIO OUT]

01:00:26.152 --> 01:00:27.610
RICARDO HAUSMANN:
--enough pressure

01:00:27.610 --> 01:00:33.340
on the armed forces for them
to return to the Constitution.

01:00:33.340 --> 01:00:37.450
They are allowing
president Maduro

01:00:37.450 --> 01:00:38.920
to violate the Constitution.

01:00:38.920 --> 01:00:41.290
To assert power.

01:00:41.290 --> 01:00:45.340
To govern without the
authorization of the National

01:00:45.340 --> 01:00:49.450
Assembly, without any
respect to the Constitution.

01:00:49.450 --> 01:00:51.850
They should just go back
to the Constitution.

01:00:51.850 --> 01:00:59.960
And you can convince them by
forcing them to repress you.

01:00:59.960 --> 01:01:02.210
By putting your people
in danger every day.

01:01:02.210 --> 01:01:05.030
To go to the streets to protest.

01:01:05.030 --> 01:01:10.940
By appealing to their humanity.

01:01:10.940 --> 01:01:16.940
By negotiating their
future role in society.

01:01:16.940 --> 01:01:20.930
But, you know, what you
said about the FARC,

01:01:20.930 --> 01:01:23.150
is that the reason
why they negotiated

01:01:23.150 --> 01:01:26.590
is because they
were under threat.

01:01:26.590 --> 01:01:29.550
And we don't have
that instrument.

01:01:29.550 --> 01:01:31.410
We cannot threaten them.

01:01:31.410 --> 01:01:34.290
They are armed,
we are not armed.

01:01:34.290 --> 01:01:39.980
So it makes the negotiation
or process difficult.

01:01:39.980 --> 01:01:43.350
And you're also unable
to promise them much.

01:01:43.350 --> 01:01:45.120
Because they have
nothing to give.

01:01:45.120 --> 01:01:47.190
And you have no
credibility in being

01:01:47.190 --> 01:01:51.100
able to deliver on
any promises you make.

01:01:51.100 --> 01:01:54.590
So that's why it's hard, without
international involvement,

01:01:54.590 --> 01:01:57.720
to change the situation.

01:01:57.720 --> 01:02:01.500
Well now let me get back
to my role as moderator.

01:02:10.690 --> 01:02:14.440
Well, let's start
with an easy one.

01:02:14.440 --> 01:02:16.930
My name is Juan David
Gutierres, and I am originally

01:02:16.930 --> 01:02:19.840
from Armenia, Colombia.

01:02:19.840 --> 01:02:21.610
This is the first
time I verbalize

01:02:21.610 --> 01:02:26.330
that I am proud of a Colombian
president because of you.

01:02:26.330 --> 01:02:27.940
Thank you for
bringing Colombia back

01:02:27.940 --> 01:02:30.010
to a positive conversation.

01:02:30.010 --> 01:02:34.030
My question relates to the
impact of the peace process.

01:02:34.030 --> 01:02:36.370
Historically oppressed and
marginalized communities

01:02:36.370 --> 01:02:37.030
in Colombia.

01:02:37.030 --> 01:02:41.170
In essence, I'm talking about
Afro Colombian and indigenous

01:02:41.170 --> 01:02:43.960
groups, who have certainly
been the most affected

01:02:43.960 --> 01:02:45.370
by the conflict.

01:02:45.370 --> 01:02:48.915
How to turn these dominant
narratives of hate?

01:02:48.915 --> 01:02:50.540
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS:
Very good question.

01:02:56.560 --> 01:03:02.380
The peace has two faces,
two sort of trenches.

01:03:02.380 --> 01:03:06.650
First, is what they call
peace making, which is the one

01:03:06.650 --> 01:03:09.710
that we already delivered.

01:03:09.710 --> 01:03:10.490
We've made peace.

01:03:10.490 --> 01:03:12.170
We signed the agreement.

01:03:12.170 --> 01:03:14.430
The FARC gave up their arms.

01:03:14.430 --> 01:03:17.340
The arms went to the [INAUDIBLE]
nations that were destroyed.

01:03:17.340 --> 01:03:20.210
The FARC are now
a political party.

01:03:20.210 --> 01:03:25.160
And their members are being
re incorporated into society.

01:03:25.160 --> 01:03:30.540
The other part is
peace building.

01:03:30.540 --> 01:03:34.050
Which is even more
difficult than peacemaking.

01:03:34.050 --> 01:03:37.740
I will tell you an anecdote.

01:03:37.740 --> 01:03:43.050
One of my big allies in the
peace process was the pope.

01:03:43.050 --> 01:03:45.690
And I used to go visit him.

01:03:45.690 --> 01:03:50.000
And I used to tell
him, your holiness,

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:52.160
why don't you go to
Columbia and give me a push?

01:03:52.160 --> 01:03:54.530
I need it.

01:03:54.530 --> 01:03:58.610
And he smiled I said,
I will go to Columbia

01:03:58.610 --> 01:04:01.490
when you will most need me.

01:04:01.490 --> 01:04:04.760
And he went to
Columbia's historic visit

01:04:04.760 --> 01:04:08.660
after the peace process
had already been signed.

01:04:08.660 --> 01:04:12.750
After the arms had
been destroyed.

01:04:12.750 --> 01:04:17.600
And he went in a visit
that he, himself,

01:04:17.600 --> 01:04:23.230
baptized as, I am going
to Columbia to give

01:04:23.230 --> 01:04:25.810
a push to the Colombians.

01:04:25.810 --> 01:04:28.630
To take the first step towards--

01:04:28.630 --> 01:04:33.820
and these are the magic
words-- towards reconciliation.

01:04:33.820 --> 01:04:39.400
Reconciliation with the victims.

01:04:39.400 --> 01:04:42.520
Reconciliation among
Colombians that

01:04:42.520 --> 01:04:45.700
have been hating each
other for so many years.

01:04:45.700 --> 01:04:51.580
Reconciliation with all those
vulnerable sectors of society

01:04:51.580 --> 01:04:55.210
that, because of the
war, had been neglected.

01:04:55.210 --> 01:04:58.780
And even reconciliation
with the environment.

01:04:58.780 --> 01:05:03.910
Because the war has
also terrible effects

01:05:03.910 --> 01:05:05.050
in our biodiversity.

01:05:05.050 --> 01:05:07.360
And Colombia is one of
the most when the richest

01:05:07.360 --> 01:05:10.750
countries in the world, in
terms of the environment

01:05:10.750 --> 01:05:14.100
and biodiversity.

01:05:14.100 --> 01:05:21.120
So what is happening, and some
reforms have been approved,

01:05:21.120 --> 01:05:26.490
is to give these vulnerable
sectors of society

01:05:26.490 --> 01:05:28.830
much more space.

01:05:28.830 --> 01:05:32.580
And guarantee their rights.

01:05:32.580 --> 01:05:37.130
For example, the
indigenous people,

01:05:37.130 --> 01:05:39.350
the indigenous communities.

01:05:39.350 --> 01:05:45.740
We have been giving them
more autonomy in their health

01:05:45.740 --> 01:05:48.410
systems, in their
education systems.

01:05:48.410 --> 01:05:55.070
And in their special
justice that they apply.

01:05:55.070 --> 01:05:58.400
And this is a process
that is going on.

01:05:58.400 --> 01:06:03.080
And now that we have peace,
this should accelerate.

01:06:03.080 --> 01:06:05.330
So it's a process
that it started.

01:06:05.330 --> 01:06:08.330
And thanks to the
peace process, this

01:06:08.330 --> 01:06:11.900
is something that
is now possible.

01:06:11.900 --> 01:06:13.570
RICARDO HAUSMANN: Very good.

01:06:13.570 --> 01:06:15.980
And I have a question
here from Juan Miguel.

01:06:15.980 --> 01:06:21.500
He asks, essentially, why
was Colombia so divided

01:06:21.500 --> 01:06:25.973
about the peace agreement?

01:06:25.973 --> 01:06:27.806
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS:
That is a good question.

01:06:27.806 --> 01:06:34.340
And peace processes
always have enemies.

01:06:38.720 --> 01:06:42.650
I remember President
Clinton telling me

01:06:42.650 --> 01:06:52.020
that he mentioned this anecdote
in the funeral of McGuinness,

01:06:52.020 --> 01:06:56.520
one of the leaders of the
Northern Ireland peace process,

01:06:56.520 --> 01:07:01.410
that in the middle of the
peace process in South Africa,

01:07:01.410 --> 01:07:04.160
Mandela called Clinton.

01:07:04.160 --> 01:07:10.310
And he said, Mr. President,
they are really destroying me.

01:07:10.310 --> 01:07:13.250
The criticism is very harsh.

01:07:13.250 --> 01:07:17.960
And he said, well,
this is to be expected.

01:07:17.960 --> 01:07:20.620
The apartheid people
don't like you.

01:07:20.620 --> 01:07:23.900
He said, no, no, no, it's
my own people, the ones that

01:07:23.900 --> 01:07:27.960
are criticizing me.

01:07:27.960 --> 01:07:36.430
Peace, you have to define,
what is the difficult decision

01:07:36.430 --> 01:07:40.930
is, where do you draw the line
between peace and justice?

01:07:40.930 --> 01:07:44.160
And no matter where
you draw it, you

01:07:44.160 --> 01:07:49.650
will have people
dissatisfied from both sides.

01:07:49.650 --> 01:07:52.500
People who don't
understand the concept

01:07:52.500 --> 01:07:53.910
of transitional justice.

01:07:53.910 --> 01:07:56.400
This is a different
type of justice

01:07:56.400 --> 01:07:59.070
that is applied to
peace processes,

01:07:59.070 --> 01:08:04.590
like the Colombians, where
the perpetrators of war crimes

01:08:04.590 --> 01:08:06.960
don't go to a normal jail.

01:08:06.960 --> 01:08:11.880
They are sanctioned to repair
the rights of the victims.

01:08:11.880 --> 01:08:15.140
And this is difficult to
understand by many people.

01:08:15.140 --> 01:08:20.390
Also, many people take
advantage politically

01:08:20.390 --> 01:08:24.020
of this dissatisfaction
from both sides.

01:08:24.020 --> 01:08:27.140
And I tell you,
there's a professor

01:08:27.140 --> 01:08:32.390
in California called Jared
Diamond who is very well known.

01:08:32.390 --> 01:08:34.310
And he went to Columbia.

01:08:34.310 --> 01:08:37.870
And he said, I want
to see the president.

01:08:37.870 --> 01:08:40.910
And I said, of course.

01:08:40.910 --> 01:08:44.112
And he went and said, Mr.
President, I congratulate you.

01:08:44.112 --> 01:08:44.779
And I said, why?

01:08:44.779 --> 01:08:48.229
Because everybody hates you.

01:08:48.229 --> 01:08:50.180
And I said, what do you mean?

01:08:50.180 --> 01:08:53.540
And he said, I've been
talking to both sides.

01:08:53.540 --> 01:08:54.950
Both sides are dissatisfied.

01:08:54.950 --> 01:08:57.500
That means that the
agreement that they made

01:08:57.500 --> 01:08:59.060
is a good agreement.

01:08:59.060 --> 01:09:03.410
And so it takes time
for people to appreciate

01:09:03.410 --> 01:09:05.390
the benefits of peace.

01:09:05.390 --> 01:09:10.160
And to heal the wounds
that so many years of war

01:09:10.160 --> 01:09:12.098
have produced.

01:09:12.098 --> 01:09:14.390
RICARDO HAUSMANN: Well, it's
been less than a year now.

01:09:14.390 --> 01:09:16.000
But is it holding?

01:09:16.000 --> 01:09:17.250
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: Well, yes.

01:09:17.250 --> 01:09:24.729
This process is irreversible
Nobody in their right mind

01:09:24.729 --> 01:09:28.210
can think that FARC we
go back to the mountain.

01:09:28.210 --> 01:09:30.520
They have surrendered
their arms.

01:09:30.520 --> 01:09:35.319
They are now reintegrated into
politics and in normal life.

01:09:39.691 --> 01:09:41.649
The problem with the
peace process in Colombia,

01:09:41.649 --> 01:09:44.770
it's probably the most
comprehensive peace process

01:09:44.770 --> 01:09:46.029
ever negotiated.

01:09:46.029 --> 01:09:50.020
And I don't say this,
all the experts say,

01:09:50.020 --> 01:09:56.810
there are two elements
that are very sui generis.

01:09:56.810 --> 01:10:01.010
Very sophisticated,
transitional, justice system.

01:10:01.010 --> 01:10:05.570
And it's the first time
that the peace process

01:10:05.570 --> 01:10:09.140
agrees on development plans
for all the regions that

01:10:09.140 --> 01:10:10.760
were affected by the conflict.

01:10:10.760 --> 01:10:16.250
Which has 15 years
to be complied with.

01:10:16.250 --> 01:10:20.480
People are very anxious that
the road is going to come,

01:10:20.480 --> 01:10:23.420
when the school is
going to be built.

01:10:23.420 --> 01:10:28.100
And that it is going
to take some time.

01:10:28.100 --> 01:10:31.220
But the process,
itself, is irreversible.

01:10:31.220 --> 01:10:35.210
And legally, there is
something which people forget.

01:10:35.210 --> 01:10:38.030
Our Constitutional
Court made a ruling

01:10:38.030 --> 01:10:42.530
that no president, no
Congress, for the next three

01:10:42.530 --> 01:10:45.860
presidential
periods, can approve

01:10:45.860 --> 01:10:50.960
a law that will go against the
compliance of the agreement.

01:10:50.960 --> 01:10:52.980
RICARDO HAUSMANN: I
have two questions here,

01:10:52.980 --> 01:10:56.550
that have an
international flavor.

01:10:56.550 --> 01:11:00.060
One comes from
Bilbao, Spain where,

01:11:00.060 --> 01:11:02.460
you know the
problems they've had

01:11:02.460 --> 01:11:05.490
with [INAUDIBLE]
nationalist terrorism.

01:11:05.490 --> 01:11:10.110
Question is this is, it worth
to sacrifice justice for peace?

01:11:10.110 --> 01:11:14.480
I would like to hear your
personal point of view.

01:11:14.480 --> 01:11:16.800
And so that's the
first question,

01:11:16.800 --> 01:11:20.700
coming from justice
versus peace.

01:11:20.700 --> 01:11:25.890
The second one is, you spoke of
defeating FARC and commencing

01:11:25.890 --> 01:11:27.510
a peace process with them.

01:11:27.510 --> 01:11:32.390
What advice would you give
to the leaders of Israel?

01:11:35.330 --> 01:11:42.050
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS:
Well, the instructions

01:11:42.050 --> 01:11:50.050
I gave my negotiators was, go
and negotiate as much justice

01:11:50.050 --> 01:11:54.150
as you can, that will
allow peace to be made.

01:11:57.760 --> 01:12:03.070
And among the negotiators, there
was an American negotiator.

01:12:03.070 --> 01:12:07.720
A professor from the
University of Notre Dame.

01:12:07.720 --> 01:12:12.550
Name was Douglass Cassel,
expert in human rights.

01:12:12.550 --> 01:12:17.250
And his role in the
negotiation was,

01:12:17.250 --> 01:12:20.880
I want to comply with
our own constitution

01:12:20.880 --> 01:12:23.800
and with international law.

01:12:23.800 --> 01:12:26.370
So everything that
we negotiated,

01:12:26.370 --> 01:12:30.560
from the justice
point of view, is

01:12:30.560 --> 01:12:33.980
a sacrifice for
the people that are

01:12:33.980 --> 01:12:36.440
accustomed to normal justice.

01:12:36.440 --> 01:12:42.740
But it's within the range
of the acceptable justice

01:12:42.740 --> 01:12:44.240
in today's world.

01:12:44.240 --> 01:12:49.070
The International Criminal
Court was the product

01:12:49.070 --> 01:12:51.130
of the Rome statute.

01:12:51.130 --> 01:12:52.870
And the International
Criminal Court

01:12:52.870 --> 01:12:59.490
says what we negotiated
is sufficient to guarantee

01:12:59.490 --> 01:13:02.370
that there will be no impunity.

01:13:02.370 --> 01:13:04.670
Especially for the
most responsible

01:13:04.670 --> 01:13:12.240
of war crimes and
crimes against humanity.

01:13:12.240 --> 01:13:18.108
What advice would I give
the leaders of Israel?

01:13:18.108 --> 01:13:30.980
Well, first, to stop advancing
in those things that are making

01:13:30.980 --> 01:13:34.940
this two state solution viable.

01:13:34.940 --> 01:13:37.720
If you continue advancing
with the settlements.

01:13:37.720 --> 01:13:42.350
If you continue
taking land, like what

01:13:42.350 --> 01:13:49.730
is happening with
the Golan Heights,

01:13:49.730 --> 01:13:55.140
make any peace agreement
much more difficult.

01:13:55.140 --> 01:13:57.600
I think, like in
any peace agreement,

01:13:57.600 --> 01:13:59.910
you need to sit down.

01:13:59.910 --> 01:14:05.830
And if there is the will, it
should not be that difficult.

01:14:05.830 --> 01:14:11.020
Because other
attempts have almost

01:14:11.020 --> 01:14:14.320
defined the two state solution.

01:14:14.320 --> 01:14:17.800
If there is the will, I think
that it will be possible.

01:14:20.892 --> 01:14:23.350
RICARDO HAUSMANN: Here is a
topic we haven't discussed yet,

01:14:23.350 --> 01:14:24.680
tonight.

01:14:24.680 --> 01:14:27.590
It says, corruption has
plagued the governments

01:14:27.590 --> 01:14:30.830
of all developing countries.

01:14:30.830 --> 01:14:34.850
What are your ideas on how to
combat it, how to control it,

01:14:34.850 --> 01:14:36.990
how to deal with it?

01:14:36.990 --> 01:14:38.490
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS:
I think the best

01:14:38.490 --> 01:14:43.890
antidote that any society
can have against corruption

01:14:43.890 --> 01:14:46.800
is education.

01:14:46.800 --> 01:14:47.850
A society that--

01:14:47.850 --> 01:14:49.266
[APPLAUSE]

01:14:49.266 --> 01:14:52.710
A society that is
well educated would

01:14:52.710 --> 01:14:57.780
be much more resistant to
leaders that are corrupt,

01:14:57.780 --> 01:15:00.480
and corruption, in general.

01:15:00.480 --> 01:15:05.400
You can also increase
the penalties,

01:15:05.400 --> 01:15:10.710
like we have done in
Colombia and many countries.

01:15:10.710 --> 01:15:16.740
But it's the values, the
principles, education,

01:15:16.740 --> 01:15:20.460
that, in the long
run, will be the best

01:15:20.460 --> 01:15:21.855
deterrent for corruption.

01:15:29.970 --> 01:15:36.060
I chaired with the prime
minister of Great Britain,

01:15:36.060 --> 01:15:37.800
with Desmond Cameron.

01:15:37.800 --> 01:15:42.030
The first anti-corruption
World Summit in London.

01:15:42.030 --> 01:15:48.330
And from there, the idea of
creating an international court

01:15:48.330 --> 01:15:50.160
against corruption.

01:15:50.160 --> 01:15:55.090
Because more and more the
corruption is multinational.

01:15:55.090 --> 01:15:59.520
It's an idea that is starting
to be discussed in the United

01:15:59.520 --> 01:16:00.020
Nations.

01:16:00.020 --> 01:16:02.260
And in certain areas.

01:16:02.260 --> 01:16:10.710
That could be a complement to
the anti-corruption polices

01:16:10.710 --> 01:16:14.330
that each country
should Put in place.

01:16:14.330 --> 01:16:16.190
RICARDO HAUSMANN:
I mean, there's

01:16:16.190 --> 01:16:19.590
an international dimension
in at least to two cases.

01:16:19.590 --> 01:16:25.040
There's the Foreign Corrupt
Practices Act, which makes it

01:16:25.040 --> 01:16:30.350
a crime say, in the US, for
a company to bribe abroad.

01:16:34.267 --> 01:16:38.970
And there are several cases of
Corrupt Practices in Venezuela,

01:16:38.970 --> 01:16:42.910
that are now in American jails.

01:16:42.910 --> 01:16:46.950
And there was this whole
international impact

01:16:46.950 --> 01:16:52.140
of the Brazilian
Lava Jato scandal

01:16:52.140 --> 01:16:54.855
where information was revealed.

01:16:58.720 --> 01:17:02.200
Is there now, the typical
thing that countries have done

01:17:02.200 --> 01:17:06.200
is to make government
procurement more complicated.

01:17:06.200 --> 01:17:08.390
And--

01:17:08.390 --> 01:17:10.961
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: Which
sometimes feeds corruption.

01:17:13.242 --> 01:17:14.950
RICARDO HAUSMANN: Do
you think technology

01:17:14.950 --> 01:17:16.090
might give us a hand?

01:17:16.090 --> 01:17:20.516
Or, I mean,
financial information

01:17:20.516 --> 01:17:22.130
might give us a hand?

01:17:22.130 --> 01:17:23.380
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: The best--

01:17:23.380 --> 01:17:27.760
I mean, I come from
the journalistic world.

01:17:27.760 --> 01:17:32.230
The things that the corrupt
people fear the most

01:17:32.230 --> 01:17:35.600
is the lack of public opinion.

01:17:35.600 --> 01:17:40.900
And so the more laws that
oblige the government

01:17:40.900 --> 01:17:42.830
to be transparent.

01:17:42.830 --> 01:17:45.330
To make the information public.

01:17:45.330 --> 01:17:47.940
To have the people,
the citizens,

01:17:47.940 --> 01:17:51.720
being able to see exactly how
they're spending their money,

01:17:51.720 --> 01:17:52.560
and where it goes.

01:17:52.560 --> 01:17:55.560
And how the contracts are made.

01:17:55.560 --> 01:17:58.230
That helps tremendously.

01:17:58.230 --> 01:18:00.350
The role of the
press, when there

01:18:00.350 --> 01:18:05.070
is a good press or
an inquisitive press,

01:18:05.070 --> 01:18:06.570
governments don't like it.

01:18:06.570 --> 01:18:08.170
But it's necessary.

01:18:08.170 --> 01:18:12.090
And so there's
different factors that

01:18:12.090 --> 01:18:14.850
can contribute to
fight corruption

01:18:14.850 --> 01:18:17.550
with more effectiveness.

01:18:17.550 --> 01:18:19.410
RICARDO HAUSMANN:
What are the top three

01:18:19.410 --> 01:18:21.690
most pressing economic
challenges facing

01:18:21.690 --> 01:18:24.485
Colombia today?

01:18:24.485 --> 01:18:26.110
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS:
I would say we need

01:18:26.110 --> 01:18:30.030
to diversify more the economy.

01:18:30.030 --> 01:18:35.550
We still are too much
dependent on raw materials,

01:18:35.550 --> 01:18:36.795
basic commodities.

01:18:39.960 --> 01:18:43.140
We need to increase
our productivity.

01:18:43.140 --> 01:18:48.480
All of Latin America has a
problem with productivity.

01:18:48.480 --> 01:18:56.130
If you compare the productivity
in the Asian countries

01:18:56.130 --> 01:19:00.420
compared to Latin America,
the growth component

01:19:00.420 --> 01:19:03.060
of productivity in Asia
is much, much higher

01:19:03.060 --> 01:19:05.040
than in our countries.

01:19:05.040 --> 01:19:08.400
So there you have a
problem, but it's also

01:19:08.400 --> 01:19:12.010
an opportunity to grow faster.

01:19:12.010 --> 01:19:16.680
And I would, again, concentrate
more and more in education.

01:19:16.680 --> 01:19:19.550
Because education also helps.

01:19:19.550 --> 01:19:29.970
If you give everybody a good
and level starting point,

01:19:29.970 --> 01:19:32.400
you also create more equality.

01:19:32.400 --> 01:19:38.440
And more equality
is also a factor

01:19:38.440 --> 01:19:41.770
that will contribute to
our growth and to progress.

01:19:46.555 --> 01:19:49.270
RICARDO HAUSMANN: So says,
as an experienced politician,

01:19:49.270 --> 01:19:53.680
negotiator, peacemaker,
and military leader,

01:19:53.680 --> 01:19:57.640
what do you recommend
Juan Guaido to do to end

01:19:57.640 --> 01:20:01.018
the dictatorship in Venezuela?

01:20:01.018 --> 01:20:02.560
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS:
I would recommend

01:20:02.560 --> 01:20:10.310
him to use his courage
that he has demonstrated.

01:20:10.310 --> 01:20:18.150
And try to build, what they
call the Golden Bridge,

01:20:18.150 --> 01:20:21.150
for the regime that
is now in power

01:20:21.150 --> 01:20:23.710
to go away as soon as possible.

01:20:23.710 --> 01:20:28.950
But with a golden bridge,
if people think that Maduro

01:20:28.950 --> 01:20:33.210
will simply say, OK, I'm going.

01:20:33.210 --> 01:20:37.690
And he ends up in a jail
like Noriega in Panama,

01:20:37.690 --> 01:20:39.260
that will never happen.

01:20:39.260 --> 01:20:43.590
So you have to give him a
way out, a dignified way out.

01:20:43.590 --> 01:20:45.300
But in order to
do that, you need

01:20:45.300 --> 01:20:53.970
to bring in the major
stakeholders of this process,

01:20:53.970 --> 01:20:55.650
International stakeholders.

01:20:55.650 --> 01:20:57.410
Who are they?

01:20:57.410 --> 01:21:06.010
China, Russia, the US,
Cuba, and Latin America.

01:21:06.010 --> 01:21:13.750
And if he sits down with Maduro
and says, we will negotiate.

01:21:13.750 --> 01:21:20.680
You go out in transition with
the major stakeholders backing

01:21:20.680 --> 01:21:26.400
that, you will then have
a peaceful transition.

01:21:26.400 --> 01:21:30.540
Because what I fear
most is any transition

01:21:30.540 --> 01:21:32.150
which will be violent.

01:21:32.150 --> 01:21:35.250
Venezuela, and you know
that better than anybody,

01:21:35.250 --> 01:21:38.730
has many, many people armed.

01:21:38.730 --> 01:21:39.230
ChÃ¡vez.

01:21:39.230 --> 01:21:43.450
Since the very beginning,
followed the Cuban advice

01:21:43.450 --> 01:21:49.140
of arming the defenders
of the revolution.

01:21:49.140 --> 01:21:51.570
The institutions
have been destroyed.

01:21:51.570 --> 01:21:55.320
The criminal bands
have taken over parts

01:21:55.320 --> 01:21:59.400
of Venezuela, especially
the rich parts where there's

01:21:59.400 --> 01:22:01.440
gold, where there's coltan.

01:22:01.440 --> 01:22:06.420
And in order to be
able to control that,

01:22:06.420 --> 01:22:07.710
you have to avoid violence.

01:22:07.710 --> 01:22:11.520
Because if violence erupts,
to control that violence

01:22:11.520 --> 01:22:12.810
will take a long time.

01:22:15.440 --> 01:22:17.190
RICARDO HAUSMANN: I
think we probably have

01:22:17.190 --> 01:22:18.580
time for two more questions.

01:22:18.580 --> 01:22:22.780
So the first one is from
William [INAUDIBLE] says,

01:22:22.780 --> 01:22:27.780
could you explain how
Ser Pilo Paga works?

01:22:27.780 --> 01:22:29.292
And--

01:22:29.292 --> 01:22:30.750
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS:
Great question,

01:22:30.750 --> 01:22:32.490
because it's my
favorite program.

01:22:32.490 --> 01:22:34.053
Unfortunately, it--

01:22:34.053 --> 01:22:35.970
RICARDO HAUSMANN: Let
me translate it for you.

01:22:35.970 --> 01:22:38.285
Being a nerd pays off.

01:22:38.285 --> 01:22:40.350
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: Yes,
Being a good student.

01:22:43.570 --> 01:22:50.610
No, we copied that
system from Australia.

01:22:50.610 --> 01:22:53.250
There's a similar
system in Australia.

01:22:53.250 --> 01:22:54.510
What did we do?

01:22:59.860 --> 01:23:05.520
The students that graduated
with the best grades

01:23:05.520 --> 01:23:11.070
from the lower strata, the ones
that got the best grades would

01:23:11.070 --> 01:23:15.080
have the opportunity go to the
best universities in Colombia.

01:23:15.080 --> 01:23:18.340
And the state will pay.

01:23:18.340 --> 01:23:24.970
You negotiate it with the
universities and they got in.

01:23:24.970 --> 01:23:29.700
The best university in
Colombia is probably Los Andes.

01:23:29.700 --> 01:23:35.400
40%, 4-0, of the new
students came because all

01:23:35.400 --> 01:23:37.350
wanted to go to Los Andes.

01:23:37.350 --> 01:23:41.230
And they competed with
the rich kids from Bogota.

01:23:41.230 --> 01:23:46.210
And, of course, they won
their place in Los Andes.

01:23:46.210 --> 01:23:51.380
So this is a program that has
tremendous social mobility.

01:23:51.380 --> 01:23:53.850
It gives the brightest
the opportunity

01:23:53.850 --> 01:23:55.990
to go to the best universities.

01:23:55.990 --> 01:24:00.550
It improves tremendously the
quality of the education,

01:24:00.550 --> 01:24:02.380
where they go to.

01:24:02.380 --> 01:24:08.840
It's a win-win situation
from every point of view.

01:24:08.840 --> 01:24:14.840
The present government
decided to do away with it.

01:24:14.840 --> 01:24:16.850
Unfortunately, I must
say, because this

01:24:16.850 --> 01:24:19.400
is one of the best programs.

01:24:19.400 --> 01:24:24.170
It was criticized because the
public university said, well,

01:24:24.170 --> 01:24:29.870
why do the students go to the
best private universities?

01:24:29.870 --> 01:24:32.570
Well, if you're as
good as the private,

01:24:32.570 --> 01:24:35.270
then they will go
to your university.

01:24:35.270 --> 01:24:37.760
It's competition.

01:24:37.760 --> 01:24:42.200
But the way it worked
was, 40,000 kids

01:24:42.200 --> 01:24:45.530
were able to go to the best
universities in Colombia,

01:24:45.530 --> 01:24:47.420
from the lower strata.

01:24:47.420 --> 01:24:50.870
That not only changed them,
they changed the whole families.

01:24:50.870 --> 01:24:54.830
You cannot not imagine the
stories behind each kid or boy

01:24:54.830 --> 01:24:57.020
or girl that are now--

01:24:57.020 --> 01:25:02.600
I just came three weeks ago I
was the commencement speaker

01:25:02.600 --> 01:25:05.660
at the graduation of
the first promotion

01:25:05.660 --> 01:25:07.400
of [INAUDIBLE] from Los Andes.

01:25:07.400 --> 01:25:10.243
And that was a great revolution.

01:25:10.243 --> 01:25:11.660
RICARDO HAUSMANN:
So it's a signal

01:25:11.660 --> 01:25:17.850
that there is an activist
policy for social mobility.

01:25:17.850 --> 01:25:20.810
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: Well,
can you imagine the people

01:25:20.810 --> 01:25:23.120
from the lower strata
having the access

01:25:23.120 --> 01:25:25.660
to go to the best universities?

01:25:25.660 --> 01:25:27.500
That immediately
changes their lives.

01:25:31.052 --> 01:25:33.260
RICARDO HAUSMANN: This is
a question from Jared Kenny

01:25:33.260 --> 01:25:37.670
from Manchester, New Hampshire.

01:25:37.670 --> 01:25:40.370
Do you still have your
drive for journalism?

01:25:40.370 --> 01:25:43.280
And if so, are there any
stories you'd like to have,

01:25:43.280 --> 01:25:47.795
or had the opportunity
to cover as a journalist?

01:25:47.795 --> 01:25:51.680
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS: Well,
when I was in government,

01:25:51.680 --> 01:25:55.970
I really missed
being a journalist.

01:25:55.970 --> 01:25:59.105
Because I was a victim
of my colleagues.

01:25:59.105 --> 01:26:00.440
[LAUGHTER]

01:26:00.440 --> 01:26:03.050
[INAUDIBLE] some
people in government

01:26:03.050 --> 01:26:04.340
don't understand that.

01:26:04.340 --> 01:26:11.120
But a watchdog, when everything
is quiet, everything is OK,

01:26:11.120 --> 01:26:12.800
he just sleeps.

01:26:12.800 --> 01:26:16.550
When he sees something
bad, he barks or bites.

01:26:16.550 --> 01:26:20.330
And when you're
in government you

01:26:20.330 --> 01:26:26.060
complain, why don't you publish
the good things, the good news?

01:26:26.060 --> 01:26:29.500
It's a bias that
journalists have,

01:26:29.500 --> 01:26:31.480
but it's a necessary bias.

01:26:31.480 --> 01:26:37.480
And I always said that
criticism, and the jurors that

01:26:37.480 --> 01:26:42.250
were against the government,
were like a bath of cold water

01:26:42.250 --> 01:26:45.550
in the morning that wakes
you up and makes you realize

01:26:45.550 --> 01:26:49.360
that you have to work more.

01:26:49.360 --> 01:26:53.460
What stories would I cover?

01:26:53.460 --> 01:26:56.630
The American election.

01:26:56.630 --> 01:27:01.890
It's getting very
interesting, very interesting.

01:27:01.890 --> 01:27:04.820
Very good.

01:27:04.820 --> 01:27:07.130
RICARDO HAUSMANN:
Would you have a piece

01:27:07.130 --> 01:27:10.628
of advice for any of
the candidates running?

01:27:16.433 --> 01:27:17.850
JUAN MANUEL SANTOS:
Well, no, it's

01:27:17.850 --> 01:27:20.983
very difficult to give
advice for the candidates.

01:27:24.240 --> 01:27:30.090
Politics, now, is becoming
very, very different

01:27:30.090 --> 01:27:32.100
from traditional politics.

01:27:32.100 --> 01:27:36.685
When Kennedy was
elected, you see

01:27:36.685 --> 01:27:40.650
in the museum, the debates
between Kennedy and Nixon.

01:27:40.650 --> 01:27:44.390
And the importance
of the arguments.

01:27:44.390 --> 01:27:49.130
In today's world, the
emotions took over.

01:27:49.130 --> 01:27:53.540
And the arguments were
sort of left to one side.

01:27:53.540 --> 01:28:00.140
And emotions are very
easily to manipulate.

01:28:00.140 --> 01:28:09.590
Fear and hate and discrimination
and nationalism and me first.

01:28:09.590 --> 01:28:14.790
These things are very
detrimental to good politics.

01:28:14.790 --> 01:28:18.160
Politics, there's transactions.

01:28:18.160 --> 01:28:23.120
It's not a black and white.

01:28:23.120 --> 01:28:26.230
it's not as zero-sum game.

01:28:26.230 --> 01:28:30.370
In politics, you give
something and I gave something,

01:28:30.370 --> 01:28:32.920
and we both agree on something.

01:28:32.920 --> 01:28:35.350
That's the nature of
politics since the Greeks

01:28:35.350 --> 01:28:37.300
invented democracy.

01:28:37.300 --> 01:28:41.140
But what you're seeing
now, is the contrary.

01:28:41.140 --> 01:28:47.540
So I would say that
any candidate that

01:28:47.540 --> 01:28:52.250
can recuperate that
type of politics

01:28:52.250 --> 01:28:58.100
based on principles, on
values, and the value of making

01:28:58.100 --> 01:28:58.880
transactions.

01:28:58.880 --> 01:29:02.960
In the good sense of
making transactions,

01:29:02.960 --> 01:29:08.870
that makes a democracy
much more effective.

01:29:08.870 --> 01:29:11.810
Polarization, the ones
that we're seeing now

01:29:11.810 --> 01:29:15.590
in the US and all around the
world, in my country also,

01:29:15.590 --> 01:29:19.620
paralyzes the action
of government.

